\begin_layout Abstract
Applications such as computer graphics rendering, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
also computer games, to check intersection!!
\end_layout

\end_inset

path planning for robotics and finite element simulations greatly benefit
 from having an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses a given polynomial curve.
 Bézier curves (which use the Bernstein basis) are probably the most common
 choice for this, since it is guaranteed that each interval of the curve
 is contained inside the convex hull of its control points.
 However, it is known that this convex hull is not the one with smallest
 volume, causing therefore great conservatism in all the applications mentioned
 before.
 This paper derives and presents the MINVO basis, a polynomial basis that
 generates the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses any given polynomial curve.
 We show that the MINVO basis is able to obtain a volume that is 
\begin_inset Formula $2.36$
\end_inset

 times smaller when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $903$
\end_inset

 times smaller when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

.
 Global optimality is discussed and proven for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 using Sum-Of-Squares (SOS) Programming and moment relaxations.
 
\end_layout

