\begin_layout Section
Related work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A work that attempted to solve exactly the same problem proposed in this
 was the work by Gary Herron 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herron1989polynomial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this work, the author imposed a specific structure in the form for the
 polynomials of the basis, and then solved the associated nonconvex optimization
 problem over the roots of those polynomials.
 For this specific form of the polynomials, a global minimizer was found
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, and local minimizer was found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, but no global optimality was proven for this.
 These paper goes further, and using SOS programming, it first proposes
 the most general formulation that does not impose any specific structure
 in the form of the polynomials (apart from being SOS), proving global and
 local optimality for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then, by imposing a structure in the polynomials, we are able to able to
 find global optima for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 and local optima 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4,5,6,7$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar problem has also been studied in the hyperspectral unmixing problem
 inside the remote sensing community, which consists of trying to find,
 in a given image pixel, the proportions (or abundances) of each macroscopic
 materials (endmembers) contained in that pixel 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uezato2019hyperspectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One way to address this problem is to find the simplex with minimum volume
 that encloses a set of points (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hendrix2013minimum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 However, the fact of dealing with many data points, and not necessarily
 distributed along a polynomial curve, leads to the need of different iterative
 algorithms to solve it (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rogge2006iterative,iordache2009unmixing,velez2003iterative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

