\begin_layout Section
Conversion between MINVO, Bernstein/Bézier and B-Spline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th order polynomial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

, the MINVO, Bézier or B-Spline control points (i.e.
 the vertexes of the simplex that enclose the curve) can be obtained using
 the formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{V}_{x}=\boldsymbol{P}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{x}\right)^{-1}=\boldsymbol{V}_{y}\boldsymbol{A}_{y}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{x}\right)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\{\text{MV},\text{B},\text{BS}\}$
\end_inset

 (Minvo, Bernstein, B-Spline respectively).
 For instance to convert from MINVO control points to Bernstein control
 points we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{\text{B}}=\boldsymbol{P}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{B}}\right)^{-1}=\boldsymbol{V}_{\text{MV}}\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{MV}}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{B}}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{MV}}$
\end_inset

 are the ones in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table_matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{BS}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{\text{B}}$
\end_inset

 are available in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "qin2000general"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that all the matrices need to be expressed in the same interval (
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 in this paper).
 The code provided with this paper contains functions that generate all
 these matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions and Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work derived and presented the MINVO basis.
 The key features of this basis is that it finds the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses a given polynomial curve (Problem 1), and also finds
 the polynomial curve that is inside a given simplex, and whose coefficient
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{n},...,\boldsymbol{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 span a parallelogram with largest volume (Problem 2).
 Global optimality was also proven for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
